******
[2] Diarrhea - Nepal (Bajura District)
Date: Fri 6 Jun 2014
Source: Republica [edited]
http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=76452


With the increasing temperature, the number of people visiting the District Health Office, Bajura, has increased. Around 25 patients visit the emergency ward of the hospital daily, according to the hospital source.

Most of the patients visiting the hospital are found suffering from diarrhea. Some 70 people suffering from different diseases visit the hospital daily, of them, 25 are diarrhea patients, said Dr Dosti Regmi of the District Health Office, Bajura.

The number of patients suffering from diarrhea has increased at most of the VDCs in the district in the past few days. A large number of locals of Pandusain, Budhiganga, and Martadi are found suffering from diarrhea, it is learnt.

Public Health Officer at the Office, Gyanendra Dawadi, said that the number of diarrhea patients has increased due to consumption of decomposed food and contaminated water as water sources have become polluted and contaminated during summer season.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The cause or causes of the diarrhea are unknown. Bajura is in the Far Western Region of Nepal as seen on a district map at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bajura_District#mediaviewer/File:Bajura_district_location.png. - Mod.LL]

******
[3] Diarrhea - Nepal (Western Region)
Date: Sat 7 Jun 2014
Source: Republica [edited]
http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=76531


The flow of patients suffering from fever and diarrhea has increased to Damauli Hospital [Tanahu District] with the rise in mercury of late. The number of patients approaching the hospital has gone up since last mid-May [2014], said Dr Anjila Ghimire of Damauli Hospital. The rise in the number of patients is caused by unmanaged wastes and consumption of contaminated drinking water, he added.

Daily around 150 patients come to visit the hospital for treatment, said Dr Ghimire. Earlier, there was no such flow of patients to the hospital.

Mostly the patients from Byas municipality, Kahunshivapuri, Ghansikuwa, Pokharibhanjyang, and Camin of Tanahu district and from Lamjung and Gorkha [districts] are coming to receive treatment service from the hospital, said the hospital sources.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The cause of the diarrhea is not stated but is not likely to be cholera, which is generally not associated with fever.

Tanahu District is located in the Western Region as shown on a map at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tanahu_District#mediaviewer/File:Tanahu_district_location.png. - Mod.LL]
